1
00:00:30,264 --> 00:00:31,694
The Grid.

2
00:00:33,667 --> 00:00:35,307
A digital frontier.

3
00:00:37,437 --> 00:00:39,367
! tried to picture clusters of information

4
00:00:39,673 --> 00:00:41,633
as they moved through the computer.

5
00:00:43,110 --> 00:00:45,130
What did they look like?

6
00:00:45,445 --> 00:00:47,405
Ships? Motorcycles?

7
00:00:48,515 --> 00:00:50,705
Were the circuits like freeways?

8
00:00:51,051 --> 00:00:54,211
! kept dreaming of a world
! thought I'd never see.

9
00:00:56,089 --> 00:00:58,609
And then, one day...

10
00:00:58,992 --> 00:01:02,971
-You got in.
-That's right, man. I got in.

11
00:01:38,432 --> 00:01:41,622
And the world was more beautiful
than I ever dreamed

12
00:01:42,102 --> 00:01:44,472
and also more dangerous
than I ever imagined.

13
00:01:44,871 --> 00:01:46,420
Hop in bed, now, kiddo.

14
00:01:48,075 --> 00:01:50,565
-Now, I met a brave warrior.
-Tron.

15
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:55,080
Tron!

16
00:01:55,549 --> 00:01:58,009
-He fights for the users.
-He sure does.

17
00:01:58,385 --> 00:02:02,105
Oh, man, he showed me things
that no one had ever imagined.

18
00:02:02,656 --> 00:02:05,786
There were these disk battles
fought in spectacular arenas.

19
00:02:06,259 --> 00:02:08,749
Cycles that raced on ribbons of light.

20
00:02:09,128 --> 00:02:11,319
It was so radical.

21
00:02:11,665 --> 00:02:13,595
-And together...
-You built the Grid.

22
00:02:13,900 --> 00:02:17,210
We built a new grid
for programs and users.

23
00:02:18,171 --> 00:02:19,870
Now, I couldn't be in there all the time,

24
00:02:20,140 --> 00:02:24,649
so I created a program in my own image
that could think.

25
00:02:25,312 --> 00:02:27,182
Like you, and me.

26
00:02:27,481 --> 00:02:30,911
And I called him Clu.

27
00:02:31,785 --> 00:02:34,855
-Codified Likeness Utility.
-That's right.

28
00:02:35,956 --> 00:02:38,886
And Clu, Tron and I,
we built the system,

29
00:02:39,326 --> 00:02:41,956
where all information was free
and open.

30
00:02:43,163 --> 00:02:44,393
Beautiful.

31
00:02:46,867 --> 00:02:49,087
And then, one day,

32
00:02:50,404 --> 00:02:52,073
something happened.

33
00:02:54,975 --> 00:02:58,105
Something extraordinary.

34
00:03:01,181 --> 00:03:02,791
A miracle.

35
00:03:06,787 --> 00:03:07,987
What was it?

36
00:03:09,389 --> 00:03:11,879
That'll have to wait till next time.

37
00:03:12,359 --> 00:03:14,089
I gotta get to work.

38
00:03:14,361 --> 00:03:15,701
l wanna go with you, Dad.

39
00:03:15,962 --> 00:03:20,182
Yeah, well, one day you will.

40
00:03:20,801 --> 00:03:22,141
I promise.

41
00:03:22,369 --> 00:03:25,029
-To the Grid?
-Good night, Sam.

42
00:03:27,674 --> 00:03:31,244
Hey, what do you say tomorrow
you and I hit the arcade?

43
00:03:31,778 --> 00:03:34,208
You can have a crack
at the old man's high score.

44
00:03:34,581 --> 00:03:36,861
First game's on me.

45
00:03:38,452 --> 00:03:41,172
Can we play doubles?
On the same team?

46
00:03:44,124 --> 00:03:46,263
We're always on the same team.

47
00:04:08,048 --> 00:04:09,888
Good evening. Our lead story.

48
00:04:10,183 --> 00:04:14,403
ENCOM CEO and video game icon
Kevin Flynn has disappeared.

49
00:04:15,021 --> 00:04:17,741
He was best known for designing Tron
and Space Paranoids,

50
00:04:18,158 --> 00:04:20,618
the two bestselling video games
in history.

51
00:04:21,027 --> 00:04:23,806
Flynn took ownership of ENCOM
in 1982

52
00:04:24,231 --> 00:04:27,251
as the company skyrocketed
to the top of the tech industry.

53
00:04:27,701 --> 00:04:31,541
But things changed in 1985
with the untimely death of Flynn's wife,

54
00:04:32,105 --> 00:04:34,355
the mother of his young son, Sam.

55
00:04:34,708 --> 00:04:36,488
Recently, ENCOM board members

56
00:04:36,777 --> 00:04:37,917
have been troubled by reports

57
00:04:38,111 --> 00:04:40,771
of Flynn's erratic,
even obsessive, behavior.

58
00:04:41,181 --> 00:04:44,491
With Flynn missing,
the company is now in chaos.

59
00:04:44,985 --> 00:04:46,975
This afternoon, ENCOM's board

60
00:04:47,287 --> 00:04:50,126
moved to seize control
from Flynn's partner, Alan Bradley,

61
00:04:50,557 --> 00:04:53,217
vowing to return the company
to profitability.

62
00:04:53,927 --> 00:04:58,287
Loyal to the end, Bradley maintains
his belief that Flynn is not missing

63
00:04:58,932 --> 00:05:01,272
and is instead pursuing his dream of

64
00:05:01,635 --> 00:05:04,705
"a digital frontier
to reshape the human condition."

65
00:05:06,773 --> 00:05:08,943
In there is a new world,

66
00:05:09,276 --> 00:05:11,236
In there is our future.

67
00:05:11,878 --> 00:05:15,388
In there is our destiny.

68
00:05:21,655 --> 00:05:25,554
Even Flynn's most ardent supporters
are now acknowledging a difficult truth.

69
00:05:26,126 --> 00:05:28,616
Kevin Flynn may have simply
run away.

70
00:05:29,296 --> 00:05:31,726
And while Flynn's loyalists
hope for his imminent return,

71
00:05:32,098 --> 00:05:35,498
there is perhaps no one who wishes it
to happen more than young Sam Flynn,

72
00:05:36,036 --> 00:05:39,696
now in the care of his grandparents,
and heir to an empire in turmoil.

73
00:05:41,107 --> 00:05:43,537
He's coming. He promised.

74
00:05:43,910 --> 00:05:45,690
-Sam, you have to eat.
-Let go of me!

75
00:05:46,012 --> 00:05:47,182
Sam?

76
00:05:47,380 --> 00:05:50,280
What will become of Flynn's legacy
and the future of ENCOM

77
00:05:50,717 --> 00:05:51,796
will most likely depend

78
00:05:51,985 --> 00:05:54,975
on what becomes of this
now orphaned little boy.

79
00:05:57,457 --> 00:05:59,327
Sam! Come back!

80
00:06:08,768 --> 00:06:10,667
All cycle units, stand by.

81
00:06:51,611 --> 00:06:53,191
All units, stand by.

82
00:07:54,274 --> 00:07:55,824
Now that is a big door.

83
00:07:56,076 --> 00:07:57,246
Welcome, everybody.

84
00:07:57,744 --> 00:08:00,644
Please settle. I know it's late,
so I'll skip the pleasantries

85
00:08:01,081 --> 00:08:04,391
and hand things over to our chairman,
Richard Mackey.

86
00:08:06,953 --> 00:08:09,443
Thank you. Thank you.
Thank you, Claire.

87
00:08:11,658 --> 00:08:13,208
Tonight l am pleased to announce

88
00:08:13,460 --> 00:08:18,760
that ENCOM's last fiscal year
was our most profitable ever.

89
00:08:20,333 --> 00:08:21,293
Yes.

90
00:08:40,086 --> 00:08:43,186
At midnight the 12th version
of our flagship operating system

91
00:08:43,655 --> 00:08:45,766
will hit the shelves around the world.

92
00:08:47,427 --> 00:08:49,617
I'm sure it comes as no surprise
whom we have to thank.

93
00:08:50,063 --> 00:08:51,843
The head of our software design team,

94
00:08:52,132 --> 00:08:56,551
a man whose father's
own notable history with ENCOM

95
00:08:57,203 --> 00:08:59,663
helped make this company
what it is today.

96
00:09:02,509 --> 00:09:04,699
Edward Dillinger. Well done.

97
00:09:05,378 --> 00:09:06,718
Well done.

98
00:09:10,850 --> 00:09:14,390
And this year, simultaneous
to the release of ENCOM OS-12,

99
00:09:15,555 --> 00:09:20,305
we will be making our debut
on Tokyo's Nikkei Index.

100
00:09:21,027 --> 00:09:25,367
ENCOM's stock will now trade
around the world 247.

101
00:09:27,033 --> 00:09:28,403
Oh, yes.

102
00:09:52,392 --> 00:09:54,852
-Excuse me.
-Yes, Alan?

103
00:09:55,228 --> 00:09:56,598
Given the prices

104
00:09:56,830 --> 00:10:00,080
that we charge to students and schools,

105
00:10:01,468 --> 00:10:03,897
what sort of improvements
have been made in Flynn...

106
00:10:04,671 --> 00:10:07,571
I mean, ENCOM OS-12?

107
00:10:11,077 --> 00:10:13,327
This year we put a "12" on the box.

108
00:10:15,415 --> 00:10:18,454
OS-12 is the most secure
operating system ever released.

109
00:10:19,786 --> 00:10:23,185
The idea of sharing our software
or giving it away for free

110
00:10:24,157 --> 00:10:26,267
disappeared with Kevin Flynn.

111
00:10:40,206 --> 00:10:42,016
I know you're here.

112
00:10:42,775 --> 00:10:44,505
Let's make this easy.

113
00:10:47,580 --> 00:10:48,600
Come on, come on.

114
00:10:57,157 --> 00:10:58,327
Freeze!

115
00:10:59,192 --> 00:11:00,182
Okay.

116
00:11:00,627 --> 00:11:01,967
If there are no more questions,

117
00:11:02,662 --> 00:11:05,382
l would like you to meet
our next blockbuster.

118
00:11:05,798 --> 00:11:08,288
ENCOM OS-12.

119
00:11:12,438 --> 00:11:14,078
Still a few bugs.

120
00:11:14,340 --> 00:11:15,830
What's that? What is that?

121
00:11:20,246 --> 00:11:21,915
Just bear with us one sec.

122
00:11:22,182 --> 00:11:24,202
Make this go away now.

123
00:11:24,517 --> 00:11:27,147
Stop what you're doing.
Stop. Stop for one second.

124
00:11:27,554 --> 00:11:31,184
...where ENCOM's chairman,
Richard Mackey, will be launching...

125
00:11:31,724 --> 00:11:34,714
-We go live in 30 seconds.
-He's on the roof!

126
00:11:35,161 --> 00:11:37,680
-Anyone know where the master file is?
-l do.

127
00:11:39,465 --> 00:11:40,605
It's on the Web.

128
00:11:42,969 --> 00:11:44,489
We've got to stop this.

129
00:11:48,708 --> 00:11:50,757
I've got to ring that opening bell.

130
00:11:51,444 --> 00:11:53,464
-Make this stop now.
-It's locked.

131
00:11:53,780 --> 00:11:56,390
Just shut it down. Shut it down! Now!

132
00:11:56,783 --> 00:11:59,473
Relax, Mackey. Relax.

133
00:12:00,053 --> 00:12:01,103
It's under control.

134
00:12:01,287 --> 00:12:03,127
Relax? Our most valuable

135
00:12:03,423 --> 00:12:06,583
and most secure operating system
is out there for free!

136
00:12:07,060 --> 00:12:08,579
How am I supposed to explain that?

137
00:12:08,828 --> 00:12:11,458
I don't know.
Say it was all part of the plan.

138
00:12:12,832 --> 00:12:14,732
A little gift from ENCOM.

139
00:12:15,034 --> 00:12:18,694
Apparently, ENCOM Technology
is having some technical difficulties.

140
00:12:20,440 --> 00:12:23,310
Why don't we give them a chance
to sort things out?

141
00:12:50,737 --> 00:12:52,516
Hey, Dad.

142
00:12:52,839 --> 00:12:54,449
How you doing?

143
00:13:00,647 --> 00:13:03,897
-Where you gonna run to now?
-Hey, you don't wanna do that.

144
00:13:04,384 --> 00:13:06,464
Didn't anyone tell you?
Stealing is wrong.

145
00:13:06,786 --> 00:13:09,126
You can't steal
what was designed to be free.

146
00:13:09,489 --> 00:13:12,299
-Now I got you.
-Your boss is okay with this.

147
00:13:12,725 --> 00:13:13,895
The hell he is.

148
00:13:14,460 --> 00:13:16,070
Your boss works for the CEO

149
00:13:16,329 --> 00:13:17,789
and the CEO
works for the shareholders.

150
00:13:18,031 --> 00:13:20,111
Do you know
who the biggest shareholder is?

151
00:13:21,334 --> 00:13:22,794
I don't know. Some kid.

152
00:13:27,173 --> 00:13:28,723
You're Mr. Flynn?

153
00:13:30,743 --> 00:13:32,113
Why?

154
00:13:32,879 --> 00:13:35,019
This is your father's company.

155
00:13:35,348 --> 00:13:38,507
-Not anymore.
-What? Hey. Hey, kid.

156
00:13:38,985 --> 00:13:41,355
No!

157
00:13:53,566 --> 00:13:54,676
Yeah.

158
00:14:02,108 --> 00:14:03,218
You kidding me?

159
00:14:04,310 --> 00:14:07,619
-That's him! Get the team down here!
-There he is! Get him!

160
00:14:09,682 --> 00:14:11,052
What the...

161
00:14:11,484 --> 00:14:13,414
Hey! No free ride!

162
00:14:15,822 --> 00:14:16,722
No free taxi!

163
00:14:17,023 --> 00:14:18,633
You pay!

164
00:14:22,428 --> 00:14:23,858
No free ride!

165
00:14:33,639 --> 00:14:36,299
Hold it right there. Freeze!

166
00:14:38,544 --> 00:14:41,564
Okay, boys. You got me.

167
00:14:42,749 --> 00:14:43,769
Hey.

168
00:14:58,698 --> 00:15:00,568
-Hey, Karl.
-Hey, how you doing?

169
00:15:16,749 --> 00:15:18,889
Enjoy it, Marv. You earned it.

170
00:15:23,189 --> 00:15:24,829
Why are you in my apartment, Alan?

171
00:15:26,893 --> 00:15:28,763
You don't answer your phone.

172
00:15:31,464 --> 00:15:33,214
-How you been, Sam?
-Oh, you know,

173
00:15:33,499 --> 00:15:36,779
when I was 12, l appreciated
the surrogate-father thing. But come on.

174
00:15:37,937 --> 00:15:39,637
I got it all under control now.

175
00:15:41,340 --> 00:15:42,240
Clearly!

176
00:15:42,408 --> 00:15:43,548
You want to help me
with my homework?

177
00:15:43,876 --> 00:15:45,106
Like old times? Have a catch?

178
00:15:47,613 --> 00:15:50,713
You know,
you got a pretty nice view here.

179
00:15:53,653 --> 00:15:56,693
Heard you did a triple axel off of her
a few hours ago.

180
00:15:58,124 --> 00:16:00,644
-Rough landing, huh?
-Could have been worse.

181
00:16:01,027 --> 00:16:03,547
l also thought your message
to the board

182
00:16:03,930 --> 00:16:04,979
was very clever.

183
00:16:05,164 --> 00:16:07,384
Did you like that? That was Marv's idea.

184
00:16:13,306 --> 00:16:15,796
Alan, are we really
going to do this again?

185
00:16:16,943 --> 00:16:19,723
Do I really look like I'm ready
to run a Fortune 500 company?

186
00:16:20,546 --> 00:16:21,686
No.

187
00:16:22,048 --> 00:16:25,678
And truthfully, the company
is pretty happy with where you are, too.

188
00:16:26,519 --> 00:16:27,449
I bet.

189
00:16:27,653 --> 00:16:30,463
That way they can keep doing
whatever they want.

190
00:16:32,492 --> 00:16:36,411
You know, I guess what I find curious
is the crazy charities,

191
00:16:37,163 --> 00:16:39,243
the annual prank on the company.

192
00:16:39,866 --> 00:16:42,175
You have an interesting way
of being disinterested, Sam.

193
00:16:42,535 --> 00:16:44,175
Why are you here, Alan?

194
00:16:47,707 --> 00:16:49,257
l was paged last night.

195
00:16:49,542 --> 00:16:51,532
Oh, man, still rocking the pager?

196
00:16:51,944 --> 00:16:53,284
Good for you.

197
00:16:53,513 --> 00:16:57,433
Yeah, your dad once told me
I had to sleep with it, and I still do.

198
00:16:59,118 --> 00:17:01,198
Page came from your dad's office
at the arcade.

199
00:17:05,191 --> 00:17:07,331
-So?
-So?

200
00:17:08,761 --> 00:17:11,100
That number's been disconnected
for 20 years.

201
00:17:12,798 --> 00:17:15,958
Sam, two nights before he disappeared,
he came to my house.

202
00:17:16,536 --> 00:17:18,846
"I've cracked it," he kept saying.

203
00:17:19,204 --> 00:17:22,574
He was talking about genetic
algorithms, quantum teleportation.

204
00:17:23,142 --> 00:17:26,892
He said he was about to change
everything. Science, medicine, religion.

205
00:17:28,681 --> 00:17:30,731
He wouldn't have left that, Sam.

206
00:17:34,020 --> 00:17:35,250
He wouldn't have left you.

207
00:17:35,555 --> 00:17:38,715
Oh, Alan. You're the only one
who still believes that.

208
00:17:39,425 --> 00:17:41,975
He's either dead
or chilling in Costa Rica.

209
00:17:43,329 --> 00:17:44,759
Probably both.

210
00:17:45,631 --> 00:17:46,971
Look, I'm sorry.

211
00:17:47,199 --> 00:17:49,449
I'm tired, and I smell like jail.

212
00:17:50,436 --> 00:17:54,275
Let's just reconvene in another couple
of years, huh? What do you say?

213
00:17:58,778 --> 00:17:59,858
Here.

214
00:18:01,180 --> 00:18:03,320
These are the keys to the arcade.

215
00:18:04,417 --> 00:18:08,867
I haven't gone over there yet.
I thought you should be the one.

216
00:18:09,522 --> 00:18:12,542
Alan, you're acting like I'm gonna
find him sitting there working.

217
00:18:13,059 --> 00:18:16,428
Just, "Hey, kiddo. Lost track of time."

218
00:18:20,399 --> 00:18:22,268
Wouldn't that be something?

219
00:18:31,911 --> 00:18:33,171
What?

220
00:21:49,241 --> 00:21:50,761
You son of a gun.

221
00:22:31,784 --> 00:22:33,154
Flynn.

222
00:22:41,694 --> 00:22:43,444
Let's try the back door.

223
00:22:47,700 --> 00:22:48,960
What were you working on?

224
00:22:55,975 --> 00:22:57,435
LaserControl.

225
00:22:58,410 --> 00:22:59,670
Okay.

226
00:23:40,386 --> 00:23:42,255
This isn't happening.

227
00:23:58,270 --> 00:23:59,970
Oh, man, this is happening.

228
00:24:09,315 --> 00:24:10,545
Wait.

229
00:24:12,117 --> 00:24:14,137
This program has no disk.
Another stray.

230
00:24:14,453 --> 00:24:15,383
Hey, wait.

231
00:24:15,721 --> 00:24:18,031
Wait. I'm not a program!

232
00:24:47,419 --> 00:24:49,059
He actually did it.

233
00:24:52,825 --> 00:24:54,225
I'm on the Grid.

234
00:25:04,003 --> 00:25:06,993
Does the name Kevin Flynn
mean anything to you?

235
00:25:07,439 --> 00:25:09,169
Be quiet if you want to live!

236
00:25:09,441 --> 00:25:11,461
Not the games, not the games,

237
00:25:11,777 --> 00:25:13,947
not the games, not the games...

238
00:25:14,279 --> 00:25:15,509
What's his problem?

239
00:25:18,684 --> 00:25:20,264
Not the games, not the...

240
00:26:07,633 --> 00:26:09,213
Rectify.

241
00:26:12,704 --> 00:26:14,164
Rectify.

242
00:26:17,076 --> 00:26:20,326
-Games,
-No. Please!

243
00:26:20,846 --> 00:26:21,806
Rectify.

244
00:26:22,014 --> 00:26:24,674
You probably get this a lot,
but there's been a big mistake.

245
00:26:25,084 --> 00:26:26,814
Games.

246
00:26:27,086 --> 00:26:30,016
-Please, no, no.
-Hey.

247
00:26:30,456 --> 00:26:32,795
No! Erase me!

248
00:26:38,130 --> 00:26:39,970
No! Wait! Wait!

249
00:27:22,274 --> 00:27:24,174
Can somebody tell me what the...

250
00:27:28,981 --> 00:27:31,001
Hey, hey. It's got a zipper.

251
00:27:48,834 --> 00:27:50,174
He is different.

252
00:27:59,178 --> 00:28:00,198
This can't be good.

253
00:28:10,122 --> 00:28:14,482
Attention, program.
You will receive an identity disk.

254
00:28:15,227 --> 00:28:20,117
Everything you do or learn
will be imprinted on this disk.

255
00:28:21,767 --> 00:28:25,307
If you lose your disk
or fail to follow commands,

256
00:28:25,837 --> 00:28:29,237
you will be subject
to immediate de-resolution.

257
00:28:35,847 --> 00:28:38,777
Mirroring complete.
Disk activated and synchronized.

